OMG I LOVE THIS SN.  I'M SO HAPPY.

Check out new journal!!!

<lj user="barbievirus">

*Squee*

<script src="http://personaldna.com/h?k=CsBYtIuuiwJIwVj-DG-DDADA-cc92&t=Considerate+Artist">

Grr, I'm so annoyed.

I've been searching for a new SN (I've grown out of NightmareAlley), but everything I think of it taken.  >:/

Okay, so far I've tried:  QueenofSpades, SevenofSpades, QueenofHearts, QueenofDiamonds, AceofSpades, QueenofSpatulas, BananaQueen, PinkRevolver, PinkPistol, QueenofRock, Arabesque...

Obviously, I wanted something either card-related or silly.  And my plan was foiled.  x[

<s>PinkPistol_ is unused, though...I guess I'll do that.</s>  God damn it!  It's reserved!  Wtf does 'reserved' mean anyway?  *stabbity*

Well, anywhoodle...

I started over on my story, hehe.  So much for my pledge!  I decided that a.)  My characters sucked, and b.) I wanted to show a scene with the boat sinking.  It's going really well and my bubble of inspiration has returned.

Well, anyway, I'm off to make my new journal.  Toodleloo!

I'm making an outline. Which I've never really done for a story before...at least a detailed one. So I've reverted to the school-fashioned version. I've also outlined my characters (the ones that make it, muahaha). I'm totally sure you guys care. ;) Has anyone else noticed I start a lot of projects that I never finish? I have a major problem with commitment because I've got such a short attention span. But this is one that I'm determined to see through to the end: how will I ever publish a book if I can't even finish one? I'm going to try not to focus so much on the first few chapters being good and just get the damn thing finished, then polish when I'm done. This is something very hard for me to grasp. I've been doing this work-on-the-first-few-chapters-then-get-bored thing for about six years now. On other news: I saw Disney's Cars today. I thought I would either hate it or find it mediocre, but surprisingly, I loved it. And my dog is sick. His third eyelid is prominent (which is bad) and he's leaking tears nonstop (also bad). My dad doesn't think anything is wrong (my dog is still active and happy, as usual, his eyes are just funky) so he's waiting till Monday to see if we need to do anything. *Sigh*

Uhm...

Yeah.

Not much going on.

I've got all my icons uploaded...Now it's to formatting my icon journal. Joy. :) Oh, and LAST DAY OF SCHOOL. I'm still pissed at my Spanish teacher for not grading me fairly on my Spanish oral at all...There are several people complaining about missing a few words and getting C's, including myself, but then others (teacher's favorites, usually) miss a few words and get A's. Just--ugh. I've got three C's so far. I haven't gotten grades this bad since...seventh grade, I think.

Just three days left!  :D  I've got loads of studying to do, ugh.  Especially in Spanish, where I was unfairly graded for my oral...and math, where I just suck in general...and biology, where the first half was much harder than I expected...*sigh*

Anyway, my family and I went to see X-men 3.  'Twas awesome, but really sad.  I still love Hugh Jackman as Wolverine.  :P

I can't wait to leave behind my sophomore year.  I'm really welcoming a fresh start.

I wish we didn't have exams.  It's not like exams are a learning experience or anything...just a huge pain.

And I got elected the "most improved" in choir today.  :D

Wow, I've really gotten back into web design again. I'm so excited! I made a bajillion icons (thanks to the help I got from the tutorial listed in my memories)...Some House, Lost, and HP icons so far, as well as a few random ones (flowers, etc). Any other suggestions for icons? I plan on making about twenty more before I actually start my icon journal.

Okay. So I've officially started an icon community. Only...it's not finished. And it's ugly. I'm working on it though. :) So anyway...I'm going back to school tomorrow. Color me unenthused. I've got a project to do tonight (a collage for A Lesson Before Dying, which happens to be the only school-provided book I've liked this year). I wrote my mommy a poem Mother's Day. She told me I should send it to Hallmark, haha. It was rather cheesy.

tagged me with listing ten fictional characters I would have mad hawt sex with, and tag five others to do the same. So... 1. Edward or Jasper from Stephenie Meyer's Twilight. I don't care that they could be described as Gary Stus--they're both exceptionally handsome, charming, and vampires that sparkle in the sunlight. What more could you want? 2. Sawyer from the T.V. show Lost...I want me some southern lovin'. 3. Brad Pitt from Mr. and Mrs. Smith. Spies are hot. On that note, I could take Matt Damon as Jason Borne from Borne Identity who was an assassin, which is hot as well. 4. InuYasha from InuYasha...So I used to watch anime when I was younger. Shuddup. 5. Johnny Depp as Captain Jack Sparrow from Pirates of the Caribbean. Duh. I definately wouldn't mind sharing my eyeliner with Johnny Depp if that's the outcome... 6. Hugh Jackman as Logan (or Wolverine) from X-men. Rawr. 7. A young Remus Lupin from Harry Potter. Definately NOT the movie's portrayal of poor Lupin...*shudders* 8. Jack from Lost...*is running out of ideas* 9. Uhmmm...Hayden Christensen as Anakin (young 'Vader) from Star Wars. So what if he's mentally unstable and has a metal arm and becomes burnt, ugly and freakishly tall with a breathing problem? 10. CILIAN MURPHEY. Um. From....Red Eye. Or Batman Begins. Or something. But I seriously love that guy to pieces. *Drool* As for tagging people... And that's about it. Most of my other friends have quit LJ for MySpace or Xanga or whatever.

I've just had my last concert of the year, and the last concert ever at the school I'm currently going to (there was a new school built closer to where I live--it's currently called the freshman campus, but next year they are allowing grades 9-11 into the building).  So the prospect is really sorta sad.  I never mingled after the show was over--I picked up my stuff and said 'hi' to a seventh grade teacher of mine as I walked out.  It didn't really hit me until now, I suppose.  It's been a long year and I've had a lot fo ups and downs--more so than usual.

My parents gave me my first flowers ever.  :)  I'm very easy to please--give me flowers and I'll squeal in joy, even though the flowers will likely be mostly dead by the next morning. (I've never been good with plants...)

And I've got about thirteen days left in school (not counting weekends) until I am officially a junior.  A part of me wishes I was a freshman again, so I could do everything over.  Take all the classes I want to take now but don't have the time for, make all the friends I could've made, but didn't, that sort of thing. *Shrugs*

Here I am, in the school library.

*iz bored*

I haven't updated in a while, have I?  Well, I have twenty-odd days of school left, not to mention exams in the horizon, as well as the spring concert and all that fun stuff.

American Idol tonight!!  I want Elliot off.  :/

I feel like reviewing a few books. So I will. And they're rated out of five stars. Most people have loved this book, and few have though it was bad. Myself, I thought it was very entertaining--there were bits that I rolled my eyes at, I'll admit, but it was great for a first novel. The main character, Isabella Swan, is very Mary Sue-ish. She's modest, nice, shy, beautiful, a klutz, generous, and brave. The character Edward Cullen, is also very Gary Stu-ish. He's good at everything (literally), and the author can't seem to quit describing his beauty. However, she's done a Mary Sue/Gary Stu more gracefully than anyone I ever know, making them seem like dynamic, awesome characters...(and you end up wanting to beat Bella over the head to take Edward for yourself). The setting is very interesting. It's in Forks, Washington, where it rains practically all the time. Bella complains that she hates all the squashy green stuff (there's a lot of forests) and misses the blistering, dry atmosphere of Phoenix, Arizona, but I found the place sort of endearing. There is a lot of action in Twilight, specifically in the last couple of chapters. And the 500+ pages whoosh by very quickly. It is original, sweet, and generally a good book. Definitely one to check out from your library, although I wouldn't buy it unless you're a huge fan of YA vampire novels like I am. :) **** I've just finished this book, and I absolutely loved it. I'm not even religious and I loved the book to pieces. The Five People You Meet in Heaven, is about a man who dies and encounters five people in heaven (no duh) who explain his reason for existing. It's a simple, easy-to-get message--it isn't hidden under a lot of words that you have to decipher to get the true meaning of the novel, but spelled in plain English, making it a very light-hearted read. The book was very, very short (took me only a couple hours to finish), so I can't say much without giving stuff away. Trust me, though--pick it up from the library or go out and buy it. It's the most inspiring thing I've read. ***** This one is about the Ebola virus. Definitely scary--it reminds you of zombie flicks even though it's a true story. The words of the King of Horror himself: "One of the most horrifying things I've ever read. What a remarkable piece of work." -Stephen King It gets monotonical in some parts--what more can you expect from a true story? The author has no freedom to bust out his imagination; he has to tell it like it is. At the same time, however, the novel is very captivating and thrilling. And it definately makes you think. (The author only missed this bit of logic I happened to catch: he said that the Ebola virus been around as long as earth has, but then later he says it's a mystery how the virus was found on different continents...Well, all the continents were smushed together in one landmass called "Pangaea" back then. Duh.) **** This twelve-book series was disappointing. I liked them at first; it was about a boy who finds a flyer to a circus and ends up becoming a vampire's assistant. It was witty, bloody, and decently-written. But there were several factors that led to my intense dislike towards the end of the series. 1. This may be trivial, but it bugs me--these vampires don't have fangs or sharp teeth, they use the claws on their hands. And you still age, just really, really slowly. Only, if you're a half-vampire, you age faster, but still slower than most humans. Unless you have this age-splurt thing, and suddenly, you look several years older. Confusing, no? 2. Towards the middle/end of the series, the books, which were in a modern-day setting, suddenly plunge into fantasy-land, with dragons and witches and whatnot. Out of nowhere. 3. The ending was so disappointing I wanted to throw the book at the wall. *Sigh* I would only recommend the first couple of books, to be honest. The last one was a complete waste of time. **1/2 *Grins* Fun, fun.

I can't believe what Samuel L. Jackson is doing to his career. *Shakes head morosely* Come on, Snakes on a Plane? That's got to be the stupidest movie title I've ever heard of. People are saying it's a satire of action-dramas, but I dunno. I get more amusement from thinking people are really stupid enough to make a movie about snakes. On a plane. My weekend went well; I got ten dollars from my grandmother for taking a swig of Pain 100% Hotsauce. It wasn't a pleasant experience; I spent the next ten minutes waving my arms frantically and guzzling milk and shoving bread into my burning mouth. But hey, ten bucks. :D Well. *Insert ending here*

Don't new layouts make you feel all fuzzy and warm inside? I love this one, but I can't decide whether or not I liked the other one better. Hmm. Anyway, I made a list of clothes I like because I felt like it. They all come from Delia's, the best store in the world...kthxbai.

You know you're a nerd when you begin to listen to classical music. Pah. Anywhoodle...I'm stuck in a writing rut again. What else is new? These ideas keep popping up but I keep shooting them down because, hello, this is me: girl who can't focus on a plot to save her life. Buuut....I'm outlining characters, at least (several different, possible characters suitable for any sort of story line...this way, when I think of a new idea, I wouldn't have to bother with the character sketches, I could just pick a couple from my plethora of imaginary people I already created). And my setting will definately be in Florida--I want to write about that awesome state while it's still fresh in my mind. I've generally had a good week. Minus the fact that I'm having an even harder time getting out of bed than usual. I missed the bus this morning because I simply couldn't pull myself from my soft, warm covers. I made an arse of myself several times in school, too...just general stupidity, which, unfortunately, I'm very prone to. But other than that, I've been fairly happy. My friend, Hilary, whom I quit talking to awhile ago, won't shut up about how much of a bitch I am at the back of the bus, in a very loud, obnoxious voice. I told her I was done talking to her...what...two weeks ago? And she's still yammering on about it. I'm really beginning to loathe the moment I chose to be her friend in the first place. Oh well--people like her aren't really worth my time and consideration in the long run, are they? *Yawns* Well, I'm heading off to do what I do best: sleep. Night!

Why is it that these things are so accurate??! MARCH: Attractive personality. sexy. Affectionate. Shy and reserved. Secretive. Naturally honest, generous and sympathetic. Loves peace and serenity. Sensitive to others. Loves to serve others. Easily angered. Trustworthy. Appreciative and returns kindness. Observant and assesses others. Revengeful. Loves to dream and fantasize. Loves traveling. Loves attention. Hasty decisions in choosing partners. Loves home decors. Musically talented. Loves special things. Moody. How strange.

I'm baaaack!  An entire week without <s>complaining</s> blogging...It's a record.

A lot has happened since I was gone.  I'm surprised my e-mail hasn't exploded.

Basically, we went to Disney, which was loads of fun.  It's interesting how most of the rides were built towards learning things, or being memorable...They were fairly thrill-free for the most part, which isn't usually my style, but it was nice as well.  I personally loved the Animal Kingdom, and I especially liked how most of the animals had no cages (lions and gorillas obviously had barriers seperating them from the populace), and were given a large area to roam.  It was a tad disappointing with the lack of things to do, but that should have been expected, seeing as it's the newest addition.  My second favorite park was MGM, which is mostly designed for special effects and thrills, I think.  Epcot was a thrid favorite.  Magical Kingdom was alright, but being mostly directed towards children, there wasn't a lot for the adults to do.

Then, we went to the beach (Clearwater, an island off of Florida on the Gulf of Mexico, connected by a highway), where I fried.  Literally.  My nose and cheeks were like a giant water blister--I know, gross--and my cheeks were bright red.  My dad nicknamed me "Puffalump". :(

I've tanned down quite a bit, fortunately, but I've got scabs on my cheeks and nose from where the water blisters were.  And my shoulders and chin are peeling.  Trust me, I'm not entirely enthusiastic to go to school tomorrow.

We went on a pirate ship, as well!  It had three levels; the main level was the one the kids played on, the second level had adults and teenagers, and the third level was adults only...Someone had mistaken me for a mother--I hope I don't look that old!  We went on it during the sunset--so predictably, the view was beautiful; I even saw a dolphin.  I also danced a bit--they were playing things like the macarana and YMCA--I couldn't resist.  :o)  They managed to shove a pirate hat on my head in the end, even though I initially refused--and I definately said "no" to them painting a mustache on my face (I did have to walk back to our hotel!), but I let them paint a heart on my cheek (to which my mother said, "What kind of a pirate has a heart tattoo?"  and I answered, "A Kelsey kind of pirate!").

So now we're back in Indiana--supposedly the coldest state in the US at the moment (about 30 degrees), which is quite a shock from the 80+ degree weather in Florida.

My friend called me, but I'm not sure if I want to talk to her.  I'm pretty much done with listening to her drama, and I'm still in a rather pissy mood towards her, but...I dunno...I have a habit of clinging to friends I don't even like sometimes, a habit I really need to drop.

Erm, my fingers are tired now.  So here I (finally) end this entry.  Farewell!

Your Five Factor Personality Profile
Extroversion:

You have medium extroversion.
You're not the life of the party, but you do show up for the party.
Sometimes you are full of energy and open to new social experiences.
But you also need to hibernate and enjoy your "down time."

Conscientiousness:

You have medium conscientiousness.
You're generally good at balancing work and play.
When you need to buckle down, you can usually get tasks done.
But you've been known to goof off when you know you can get away with it.

Agreeableness:

You have medium agreeableness.
You're generally a friendly and trusting person.
But you also have a healthy dose of cynicism.
You get along well with others, as long as they play fair.

Neuroticism:

You have high neuroticism.
It's easy for you to feel shaken, worried, or depressed.
You often worry, and your worries prevent you from living life fully.
You tend to be emotionally reactive and moody. Your either flying very high or feeling very low.

Openness to experience:

Your openness to new experiences is high.
In life, you tend to be an early adopter of all new things and ideas.
You'll try almost anything interesting, and you're constantly pushing your own limits.
A great connoisseir of art and beauty, you can find the positive side of almost anything.
The Five Factor Personality Test
I found the worrying bit very accurate...I probably do need to lighten up. @_@ Anyhoodle, (that's officially my new word) I got the 'Student of the Month' award--which is very, erm, surprising, to say the least...especially considering my grades have dropped (Two C's! I'm horrible! One is explainable--we had a horrid Spanish teacher for a semester and now we've got a good one, and the other grade I got a C in was math and I really didn't expect any different, but still--TWO!). Although one note of happiness concerning my grades is that most of the people in my honors English class--including the people who usually get straight A's--got C's while I have a B in the class. My 'friend' said that I always look down on her like I think I'm better and the way I hold myself and talk is 'all condescending'...and not just to her, but to everyone. And--get this--she's telling me this as my 'friend' because, later in life, I won't get hired because of the way I present myself. Wtf? Like that had to do with anything in the argument... I'm probably one of the least judgemental person(s?) in the world, and if she knew me half as well as she says she does, she'd know that. And I know perfectly well what I look like in the hallways and crap--emotionless unless I'm with a friend (and unless it's her, I'm usually laughing with them). All of my other friends agree--they told me what she was saying was complete BS and I don't need to associate myself with her. Actually, before I told them the conversation, I asked, "I know this sounds weird, but do you think I look like I'm stuck up?" and they rose their eyebrows and said "Not at all, who told you that?" ...It's fairly new to me. A lot of people have said I look depressed or sickly, but never have I heard stuck-up. Oh, and I told her she was being a bitch, and she went "So? I know I'm a bitch." I said, "Well, that's not exactly something to be proud of." And she replied, "I'm not proud of it, it's just a fact of life. Get over it." *Headdesk* Have I ever mentioned how much I hate expressions like that? And why do people take pride in being a bitch? I think it says much more of a person to be kind-hearted...Sure, I joke around about being a bitch as much as the next person, but she was serious. And I'm fairly sure she *does* take pride in it, despite what she said. /End drama /End rant

I know, I know, I need to update with chapter four...Especially with spring break coming soon...:/

*Dramatic sigh*

This is why I hate MySpace.

I go on there, and some kid asked why people hated emos.  I answered, saying why people generally disliked them.  Predictably, someone took it wrong, as if I was stereotyping "emo" people myself.

She essentially called me ugly, stupid, and a bitch.  Then when I replied to her, calling her immature for saying I was ugly and that I wasn't saying I hated "emo" people or anything, she called me an ugly whore and went on and on about how I have no friends, etc.

The fact that she's a cheerleader and sits in front of me in world history makes this ten times worse.

It's like seventh grade all over again.  And I feel completely stupid and weak and everything--I'd like to say that people saying shit like that doesn't bother me--but it does.

*crosses fingers* SNOW DAY, PLEASE! Oddly enough, the day of spring decided to bring a shitload of snow, supposedly. According to the weatherman, about 4-6 inches. I love how rumors spread around my school too, especially when it comes to possible snow days: Kid 1: I hear they're gonna let us out early. (Me: Psh. Only if half the student population was in danger of spontaneously exploding from snowfall, I doubt they'd ever let us out.) Kid 2: I hear that it's gonna be the worst blizzard we've had since 1978! Kid 3: There's gonna be a snowday tomorrow, didja hear? Kid 4: Since the PLC day is tomorrow, and if we have a two hour delay, we get three extra hours of sleep! What's worse is, we've already got an hour delay (teacher shave a monthly meeting in the morning called the PLC day), and kids are still running around screaming about getting days off. I find it hilarious. Now, for TF&U, I, um, haven't started yet. Trust me when I say I've been swamped. Hopefully I'll manage to pop it in by the weekend, seeing as I got my final draft finished a few days before it's due.

*iz ded* What a horrid day for a Friday. My Spanish teacher probably thinks I'm an idiot because I had no idea by what she meant when she said 'replace the noun with a pronoun'. And then I got my essay back from being peer-edited (which I loathe, by the way), and there were so many markings in there that I was surprised the girl didn't run out of ink. Okay, so I changed tenses a few times, didn't cite things right, used commas in the wrong places, made some sentences sound awkward... Despite this, I found the energy to update. :o) New chapter! Okay, so it's kinda transition-ish. I also changed some aspects of the other story I'm trying to outline right now. I decided it would still be in the future, but only thirty years ahead or so...and the guy's name will be Ace instead of Dante. The idea, if any of you actually care, was actually sparked by V for Vendetta, which I am DYING to see, by the way...

...I really need to stop this procrastination habit of mine. I spent all night working on a 5-7 page report that was due today. That's just pathetic. I obviously need to get myself back into gear and haul ass on my school work before I start falling behind further than I already have. (Of course, I'll say this, and plan on it, but never actually do it...*sigh*). I've outlined my new story a bit further. I'm really liking it so far--I've mixed some of my older ideas with new ones and melded it into one, I suppose. It's basically got a messed up and dark(er) version of Beauty and the Beast or Romeo and Juliet type feel. The main character is Sera, and Dante is the guy she falls, reluctantly, in love with. At first, I had planned on Dante being some kind of version of the devil, and his followers were demons, but then I'd have to include angels or something, and I'd feel like I'm copying this absolutely wonderful story on Fictionpress.com, which also features doomed love, angels and demons. (Actually, if you want to read her first story, The Contract, go here.) Trust me when I say it's orgasmic in its awesomeness.

Japanese Spiderman! Complete with robots, Mexicans, and bullet-firing guitars! :D Anyhoodle. I had to stay home today because after I woke up, took a shower, and crawled back into bed to watch the news, I had accidentally fallen back to sleep. Oops. I've been plagued by a gazillion ideas for (original) story writing, but I still haven't gotten past the third page of that other one I was working on...with the boarding school or something. Although, I really don't like the idea as much as I used to. Now, I'm kinda digging a much more mature, doomed romance feel with a fair bit of horror. I could probably do a first person POV with the girl, who's horrified by this guy but lusts for/loves him at the same time. I'd start writing the outline, but hardly have time to do anything other than slave around the house. And because my English teacher likes to multitask, making us worry about homework, books, reports and tests all at once, we've got a seven page research paper we're doing as well. *sigh* I chose to do pollution and its affects on the environment. Anyway, I'm feeling a lot better than I have all week. I've been stressing myself out over loads of tests and homework, but now that all of that's over with, I should have a relatively peaceful 3-day weekend :)

I hate having to debate about something I really don't give a flying fuck about.

Okay, in history, we're having to debate over who discovered the Americas first:  Columbus, the Vikings or the Chinese.

Firstly, I think saying that any of these guys "discovered" land that was already inhabited by Native Americans is stupid.

Secondly, my group was stuck with the Chinese.  I don't know nor care whether they discovered it first, and I can't be assed enough to figure it out.

Maybe if she gave us topics like abortion or something, I'd be able to present a good argument.  But instead, my teacher gives us a topic that none of the students care about.  *sighs, and submerges back into boring page of information*
